\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces (a) Small sample of an a-SiO$_2$ structure created from a melt-quench technique showing the Si-O tetrahedral bond network. Bond lengths range between 1.6 and 1.8 $\r A$. (b) Small sample of an a-Si structure created by the modified WWW algorithm. Bond lengths range between 2.3 and 2.7 $\r A$. Visualizations using the VESTA package with blue silicon atoms and red oxygen atoms.\cite {momma_vesta:_2008} }}{82}{figure.4.1}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces Vibrational DOS of a-SiO$_2$ and a-Si plotted on a log-log scale. Both models show an $\omega ^{2}$ scaling at low frequency. The DOS for a-Si has two peaks similar to the DOS of the crystalline phase.\cite {landry_effect_2010} The DOS for a-SiO$_2$ is flat over most of the spectrum, with a high frequency gap that separates the Si-O interactions.\cite {mcgaughey_thermal_2004} }}{85}{figure.4.2}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces Longitudinal (left panel) and transverse (right panel) structure factors [Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:SLT}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}] for (a) a-SiO$_2$ and (b) a-Si. The wavevectors are normalized by $\kappa _{max} = 2\pi /a$, where $a$ is 4.8 (a-SiO$_2$) and 5.43 (a-Si) $\r A$, based on the lattice constants of the crystalline phases. \cite {wyckoff_crystal_1963,stillinger_computer_1985} }}{88}{figure.4.3}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces Vibrational mode lifetimes predicted by NMD [Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:NMD_life}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}] and the structure factors [Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:Lorentzian_SLT}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}] for (a) a-SiO$_2$ and (b) a-Si. The NMD-predicted lifetimes are larger than the IR limit. The lifetimes predicted from the structure factors fall below the IR limit at high-frequency for a-Si and for all frequencies for a-SiO$_2$. For a-Si, a clear $\omega ^{-2}$ scaling is observed at low frequencies, while the lifetimes plateau at higher frequencies, over a wider range of frequencies than for a-SiO$_2$, with two peaks corresponding to the peaks in the DOS (Fig. \ref {FIG:DOS}). The transition from the low-frequency scaling to the plateau region for a-Si occurs near $10^{13}$ rads$/$s, which corresponds to where the DOS first peaks in Fig. \ref {FIG:DOS}.}}{94}{figure.4.4}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.5}{\ignorespaces Vibrational mode diffusivities predicted from NMD [using Eqs. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:Dtau}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} and \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:NMD_life}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} with the DOS sound speed from Table \ref {T:vs}] and the AF theory [Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:DAF}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}]. Also shown are extrapolations based on an $\omega ^{-2}$ scaling with Eqs. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:Dtau}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} and \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:tauw2}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} for a-SiO$_2$ and a-Si, and an additional $\omega ^{-4}$ scaling for a-Si. For both systems, the diffusivities are larger than the high-scatter limit [Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:D_HS}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}] except at high frequencies, where the modes are localized. }}{98}{figure.4.5}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.6}{\ignorespaces (a) Diffuson MFPs predicted from Eqs. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:Lambda}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} and \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:LambdaAF}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} and velocities (inset) predited from Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:vAF}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}} for a-SiO$_2$. (b) Diffuson MFPs and velocities predicted for a-Si. The majority of MFPs in the mid- to high-frequency range are between the simulation box size $L$ and the bond distance $a$. The high-scatter MFP is defined as $\Lambda _{HS} = a$. The MFPs and velocities approach zero only at the highest frequencies, which is an indication that the modes are localized. }}{99}{figure.4.6}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.7}{\ignorespaces Thermal conductivities of a-SiO$_2$ and a-Si predicted using the GK method and Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:kvib}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}. For a-SiO$_2$, the GK-predicted thermal conductivity is size-independent, indicating that there is not an important contribution from propagating modes. For a-Si, there is a clear size dependance, indicating the importance of propagating modes. }}{102}{figure.4.7}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.8}{\ignorespaces (a) Predicted thermal conductivity accumulation function [Eq. \textup {\hbox {\mathsurround \z@ \normalfont (\ignorespaces \ref {EQ:kLambda}\unskip \@@italiccorr )}}] for a-SiO$_2$ compared with experimental broadband frequency domain reflectance measurements by Regner et al.\cite {regner_broadband_2013} and thin film measurements from Refs. \citenum {lee_heat_1997} and \citenum {yamane_measurement_2002}. The predicted thermal conductivity accumulation demonstrates that the propagating contribution is negligible in our model, which is in accord with the experimental measurements. (b) Predicted thermal conductivity accumulation function for a-Si compared with experimental measurements by Regner et al. and thin films fabricated by sputtering (Expt. A) \cite {kuo_thermal_1992,wada_thermal_1996,cahill_thermal_1994} and chemical vapor deposition (Expt. B). \cite {hasselman_thermal_1989,moon_thermal_2002,liu_high_2009, yang_anomalously_2010} The predicted thermal conductivity accumulation demonstrates that the propagating contribution is significant for a-Si. We note that thermal conductivities as high as 6 W/m-K (not plotted) have been measured for a-Si thin films deposited using hot-wire chemical vapor deposition. \cite {yang_anomalously_2010}}}{106}{figure.4.8}
